{
  "version": "2.0.0",
  "cells": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "## **The IDL-Python Bridge**",
        "",
        "### **Definition:**",
        "The IDL-Python bridge is a two-way layer between IDL and Python. Using it, one can:",
        "- **Call Python from IDL**",
        "- **Call IDL from Python**",
        "",
        "This will allow one to expand the capabilities of IDL by using Python's huge package ecosystem. It can also be used to allow IDL code to work better with different systems."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "#### **Calling Python from an IDL script**",
        "",
        "The simplest example of the bridge calling Python from inside IDL is with its `>>>` notation. </br>",
        "This is syntactic sugar for `python.run` and thus functions the same as if you had called `python.run`."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        ">>>print(\"Hello from Python!!!\")"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "**Python.run** is very similar but it uses the Python object to run a line of Python code."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "python.run(\"print('Hello from Python!')\")"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "**Python code!**",
        "",
        "From here you can do **a lot**. More information can be found in our docs under the **Python class**."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### **Using Python Libraries**",
        "Importing libraries is as simple as importing them in Python:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "python.import, \"sys\"",
        ">>>print(sys.version)"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "But that is just asking Python to run in Python and then report back! You can also bring Python libraries to IDL using **dot notation**."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "sys = python.import(\"sys\")",
        "; IDL's help procedure",
        "help, sys.version",
        "; IDL's print procedure",
        "print, sys.version"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Our Python ships with a few libraries included natively. These include helpful libraries like `numpy` and `pandas`. However, if you want to install your own, you can use **pyutils**."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### **PyUtils**",
        "",
        "The **PyUtils** class provides a set of tools for managing your Python environment within IDL. Here are the key features:",
        "",
        "- `PyUtils.Load`: Used to manually load the IDL-Python bridge and target a specific Python version.",
        "- `PyUtils.PipInstall`: Installs a new Python package and makes it available to the embedded Python.",
        "- `PyUtils.PipUninstall`: Uninstalls the package.",
        "- `PyUtils.PipList`: Retrieves the list of installed Python packages.",
        "",
        "For a full list of functionality and keywords, please see the official documentation.",
        "```"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Let's install and use a new library! In this case, let's add `beautifulsoup4`.",
        "",
        "First we use `PyUtils` to install the library to IDL's Python:"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "pyutils.PipInstall, 'beautifulsoup4'"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Then we use dot notation to utilize the function as above!"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "bs4 = python.import('bs4')",
        "myhtml = '<html><title>IDL is great</title></html>'",
        "soup = bs4.BeautifulSoup(`${myhtml}`, 'html.parser')",
        "print, soup.title.string"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "### **Explicitly passing Variables**",
        "Sometimes it might be useful to pass a whole variable into or out of Python. This can be done with the bridge too!",
        "",
        ">IMPORTANT NOTE: IDL is **Case Insensitive**. Python is **Case Sensitive**. For this feature, IDL **lowercases** all of its Python variables. If you try to use a Python variable with uppercase letters, Python **will not see it**.",
        ""
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "content": [
        "python.PythonVarName = 30",
        "python.run, 'print(f\"(In Python) Initialized: {pythonvarname}\")'",
        "",
        "; Do some math in Python.",
        "; notice the case change",
        "python.run, \"pythonvarname *= 2\"",
        "",
        "; Back in IDL we see that the variable has changed.",
        "print, `(In IDL) After python doubles it: ${python.PythonVarName}`",
        "",
        "; now we change it in IDL.",
        "python.PythonVarName = python.PythonVarName + 10",
        "",
        "; Back in Python, we see the change.",
        "python.run, 'print(f\"(In Python) After IDL adds 10: {pythonvarname}\")'"
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "content": [
        "Do keep in mind that the Python that is part of the bridge is initialized globally. This means you might want to clean up your variables when you're done with them, depending on what you're doing."
      ],
      "metadata": {},
      "outputs": []
    }
  ]
}